# ==============================================================================
# TRIVY CONFIGURATION IGNORE FILE
# ==============================================================================
# This repository is a BC Gov quickstart template. The exceptions below address 
# static analysis warnings that are false positives for raw template variables or 
# conflict with OpenShift Container Platform runtime security behaviors.
#
# If you copy this quickstart for your own project, keep these ignores unless your 
# runtime environment or deployment registry differs.
# ==============================================================================

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# KSV-0125: Restrict container images to trusted registries
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why Ignored:
# Container registry, org, and image names are parameterized in the template files 
# (e.g. "${REGISTRY}/${ORG_NAME}/${NAME}/...") so they can be injected dynamically 
# at deploy time. Statically parsing these template strings causes Trivy to flag 
# the parameter expressions as untrusted/invalid registry URLs. The default values
# (like ghcr.io) are trusted.
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AVD-KSV-0125

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# KSV-0020 & KSV-0021: Runs with UID/GID <= 10000
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why Ignored:
# These alerts complain that the pod securityContext does not hardcode a specific 
# non-root user/group ID greater than 10000 (e.g., runAsUser: 10001). 
#
# On BC Gov's OpenShift Container Platform (Silver/Gold/Emerald clusters), the 
# Security Context Constraints (SCC) controller dynamically allocates a safe, 
# random range of extremely high UIDs/GIDs (e.g., 1000600000 to 1000609999) 
# at runtime.
#
# DO NOT resolve this by hardcoding a specific UID/GID in your manifests. Doing so 
# will cause the OpenShift admission controller to REJECT your pods because the 
# hardcoded ID won't match the namespace's allocated dynamic range.
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AVD-KSV-0020
AVD-KSV-0021

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# KSV-0011: CPU not limited
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why Ignored:
# We intentionally omit CPU limits (limits.cpu) from our container configurations.
# This aligns with BC Gov Private Cloud best practices (and the openshift-deployment
# guidelines) allowing containers to burst into unallocated node CPU capacity.
# If limits are set, containers undergo aggressive throttling during peak load.
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AVD-KSV-0011

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# KSV-0018: Memory not limited
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why Ignored:
# Standard containers define memory limits, but lightweight utility/init containers
# (e.g., wait-for-db or migrations) may omit them to prevent OOM termination of brief 
# startup tasks.
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AVD-KSV-0018
